   14→\\n    15→The plan has been substantially improved since review-01. All critical and important issues from the previous review have been addressed.\\n    16→\\n    17→## Spec Coverage Check\\n    18→\\n    19→All six fixes from the spec are covered in the plan:\\n    20→\\n    21→| Spec Fix | Plan Task | Status |\\n    22→|----------|-----------|--------|\\n    23→| Fix 1: Write prompt.txt | Task 2 | Covered |\\n    24→| Fix 2: Gemini prompt extraction | Task 1 | Covered |\\n    25→| Fix 3: Token usage | Task 3 | Covered |\\n    26→| Fix 4: Model name extraction | Task 5 | Covered |\\n    27→| Fix 5: Session metrics (turn count + duration) | Tasks 4 + 6 | Covered |\\n    28→| Fix 6: Attribution (verify existing) | Not a separate task | Spec says \\\"no code change needed\\\" - OK |\\n    29→\\n    30→No missing spec items.\\n    31→\\n    32→## New Findings\\n    33→\\n    34→### Critical (Must Fix)\\n    35→\\n    36→1. **[Task 6, line 590] `estimateSessionDuration` parses timestamp from `line.Message` -- but timestamp is a TOP-LEVEL field, not inside `message`.**\\n    37→\\n    38→   The plan's implementation does:\\n    39→   ```go\\n    40→   if err := json.Unmarshal(line.Message, &ts); err != nil || ts.Timestamp == \\\"\\\" {\\n    41→   ```\\n    42→\\n    43→   But in Claude Code JSONL, `timestamp` is at the same level as `type`, `uuid`, `message`:\\n    44→   ```\\n    45→   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"message\\\":{...},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"u1\\\",\\\"timestamp\\\":\\\"2026-01-01T10:00:00.000Z\\\"}\\n    46→   ```\\n    47→\\n    48→   The `transcript.Line` struct (`transcript/types.go:22-27`) only captures `type`, `role`, `uuid`, `message` -- it does NOT have a `Timestamp` field. So `line.Message` contains the inner message object (e.g., `{\\\"role\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"hi\\\"}`), which does NOT contain `timestamp`.\\n    49→\\n    50→   This means `json.Unmarshal(line.Message, &ts)` will always produce an empty timestamp, and the function will always return 0.\\n    51→\\n    52→   **Fix:** You cannot use the parsed `transcript.Line` structs for timestamp extraction. Instead, parse each raw JSONL line directly (before the `transcript.ParseFromBytes` call), similar to how `claudecode/lifecycle.go:268-274` does it -- unmarshal the raw line bytes, not `line.Message`. Example:\\n    53→\\n    54→   ```go\\n    55→   func estimateSessionDuration(data []byte) int64 {\\n    56→       var first, last time.Time\\n    57→       for _, rawLine := range bytes.Split(data, []byte(\\\"\\\\n\\\")) {\\n    58→           rawLine = bytes.TrimSpace(rawLine)\\n    59→           if len(rawLine) == 0 {\\n    60→               continue\\n    61→           }\\n    62→           var entry struct {\\n    63→               Timestamp string `json:\\\"timestamp\\\"`\\n    64→           }\\n    65→           if json.Unmarshal(rawLine, &entry) != nil || entry.Timestamp == \\\"\\\" {\\n    66→               continue\\n    67→           }\\n    68→           t, err := time.Parse(time.RFC3339Nano, entry.Timestamp)\\n    69→           if err != nil {\\n    70→               continue\\n    71→           }\\n    72→           if first.IsZero() {\\n    73→               first = t\\n    74→           }\\n    75→           last = t\\n    76→       }\\n    77→       if first.IsZero() || !last.After(first) {\\n    78→           return 0\\n    79→       }\\n    80→       return last.Sub(first).Milliseconds()\\n    81→   }\\n    82→   ```\\n    83→\\n    84→   This matches the existing pattern in `claudecode/lifecycle.go:261-279`.\\n    85→\\n    86→2. **[Task 6, line 533] Test data for `estimateSessionDuration` has timestamp at the wrong level too.**\\n    87→\\n    88→   The test data is:\\n    89→   ```\\n    90→   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"role\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"hi\\\"},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"u1\\\",\\\"timestamp\\\":\\\"2026-01-01T10:00:00.000Z\\\"}\\n    91→   ```\\n    92→\\n    93→   The timestamp IS at the top level here (correct for the raw line), but the implementation parses `line.Message` (wrong). So the test would actually FAIL even with this test data if the implementation uses `line.Message`. The test data is correct for the raw-line-parsing approach recommended above, but contradicts the implementation code in the plan.\\n    94→\\n    95→3. **[Task 1, line 94 and Task 4, line 380] `geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts` returns `([]string, error)`, not just `[]string`.**\\n    96→\\n    97→   The spec (line 73) has:\\n    98→   ```go\\n    99→   if prompts := geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts(data); len(prompts) > 0 {\\n   100→   ```\\n   101→\\n   102→   The plan (line 94) has:\\n   103→   ```go\\n   104→   if prompts, gemErr := geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts(data); gemErr == nil && len(prompts) > 0 {\\n   105→   ```\\n   106→\\n   107→   The plan's version is correct. However, in Task 4 (`countUserTurns`, line 380), the plan has:\\n   108→   ```go\\n   109→   if prompts, gemErr := geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts(data); gemErr == nil {\\n   110→       return len(prompts)\\n   111→   }\\n   112→   ```\\n   113→\\n   114→   This is correct Go. The spec's version would not compile. The plan correctly handles the error return in both places. No action needed -- noting this for completeness as the spec has a bug here that the plan already fixed.\\n   115→\\n   116→### Important (Should Fix)\\n   117→\\n   118→4. **[Task 4, lines 362-385] `countUserTurns` double-counts tool_result lines.**\\n   119→\\n   120→   In Claude Code JSONL transcripts, tool result messages have `\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\"` at the top level. For example, from the existing test in `attach_test.go:75-76`:\\n   121→   ```\\n   122→   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"content\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"tool_result\\\",\\\"tool_use_id\\\":\\\"tu_1\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"wrote file\\\"}]},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"uuid-3\\\"}\\n   123→   ```\\n   124→\\n   125→   This line has `line.Type == transcript.TypeUser` (i.e., `\\\"user\\\"`), so `countUserTurns` will count it as a turn. A transcript with 1 real user prompt and 5 tool calls would report 6 turns instead of 1.\\n   126→\\n   127→   The spec (Fix 5) mentions \\\"Count lines with `transcript.TypeUser`\\\" without addressing this. The spec also mentions using `geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts` length for Gemini, but does not mention filtering for JSONL.\\n   128→\\n   129→   **Fix:** Filter out tool_result lines. Check if the message content is an array containing `tool_result` blocks:\\n   130→\\n   131→   ```go\\n   132→   for _, line := range lines {\\n   133→       if line.Type == transcript.TypeUser {\\n   134→           // Skip tool_result messages -- they have type \\\"user\\\" but are not user turns\\n   135→           var msg struct {\\n   136→               Content []struct {\\n   137→                   Type string `json:\\\"type\\\"`\\n   138→               } `json:\\\"content\\\"`\\n   139→           }\\n   140→           if json.Unmarshal(line.Message, &msg) == nil && len(msg.Content) > 0 {\\n   141→               isToolResult := true\\n   142→               for _, c := range msg.Content {\\n   143→                   if c.Type != \\\"tool_result\\\" {\\n   144→                       isToolResult = false\\n   145→                       break\\n   146→                   }\\n   147→               }\\n   148→               if isToolResult {\\n   149→                   continue\\n   150→               }\\n   151→           }\\n   152→           count++\\n   153→       }\\n   154→   }\\n   155→   ```\\n   156→\\n   157→   Alternatively, reuse `extractTextFromMessage` -- if it returns non-empty, it is a real user prompt (since `extractTextFromMessage` looks for string content or text blocks, not tool_result blocks).\\n   158→\\n   159→5. **[Task 4, lines 309-313] Test data for `TestAttach_SetsSessionTurnCount` does not exercise tool_result scenario.**\\n   160→\\n   161→   The test uses a clean 2-user-message / 2-assistant-message transcript. It will pass even with the double-counting bug because there are no tool_result lines. Add a test case with tool_result lines to catch the double-counting:\\n   162→\\n   163→   ```go\\n   164→   transcriptContent := `{\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"role\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"first prompt\\\"},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"u1\\\"}\\n   165→   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"assistant\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"role\\\":\\\"assistant\\\",\\\"content\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"tool_use\\\",\\\"id\\\":\\\"tu_1\\\",\\\"name\\\":\\\"Write\\\",\\\"input\\\":{}}]},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"a1\\\"}\\n   166→   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"content\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"tool_result\\\",\\\"tool_use_id\\\":\\\"tu_1\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"ok\\\"}]},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"u2\\\"}\\n   167→   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"role\\\":\\\"user\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"second prompt\\\"},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"u3\\\"}\\n   168→   {\\\"type\\\":\\\"assistant\\\",\\\"message\\\":{\\\"role\\\":\\\"assistant\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"done\\\"},\\\"uuid\\\":\\\"a2\\\"}\\n   169→   `\\n   170→   // Expected: 2 turns (not 3)\\n   171→   ```\\n   172→\\n   173→6. **[Task 6, line 596-599] Redundant time format parsing.**\\n   174→\\n   175→   The plan parses timestamps with `time.RFC3339Nano` first, then falls back to `\\\"2006-01-02T15:04:05.000Z\\\"`. But `time.RFC3339Nano` already handles the `.000Z` format (the Go docs confirm RFC3339Nano = `\\\"2006-01-02T15:04:05.999999999Z07:00\\\"`, which matches millisecond timestamps). The existing codebase in `claudecode/lifecycle.go:274-276` falls back to `time.RFC3339` (without nano), not a custom format. Use the same pattern as the existing code:\\n   176→\\n   177→   ```go\\n   178→   t, err := time.Parse(time.RFC3339Nano, entry.Timestamp)\\n   179→   if err != nil {\\n   180→       t, err = time.Parse(time.RFC3339, entry.Timestamp)\\n   181→       if err != nil {\\n   182→           continue\\n   183→       }\\n   184→   }\\n   185→   ```\\n   186→\\n   187→### Suggestions (Consider)\\n   188→\\n   189→7. **[Task 2, line 152] Test checks the wrong path for `prompt.txt`.**\\n   190→\\n   191→   The test checks `filepath.Join(tmpDir, \\\".entire\\\", \\\"sessions\\\", sessionID, \\\"prompt.txt\\\")`. But `paths.SessionMetadataDirFromSessionID` returns a path under `.entire/metadata/` (as documented in the CLAUDE.md metadata structure section), not `.entire/sessions/`. Verify the actual path returned by `paths.SessionMetadataDirFromSessionID` and update the test accordingly, or the test will always fail with \\\"prompt.txt not found\\\" for the wrong reason.\\n   192→\\n   193→8. **[Task 5, line 429] Test data includes `model` inside `message` -- verify this is where Claude Code actually puts it.**\\n   194→\\n   195→   The test has `\\\"model\\\":\\\"claude-sonnet-4-20250514\\\"` inside the `message` JSON object. The implementation parses `line.Message` for a `model` field, which would work if the model is indeed inside `message`. However, Claude's API returns `model` at the top level of the API response, not nested inside the message body. Whether Claude Code's JSONL logger writes it inside `message` or at the JSONL line top level depends on how the agent serializes its transcript. If `model` is at the top level (like `timestamp`), then parsing `line.Message` would fail. Check a real Claude Code transcript to confirm. If `model` is at the line level, you would need the same raw-line-parsing approach as for timestamps.\\n   196→\\n   197→9. **[General] Consider extracting a `parseRawJSONLLines` helper.** Both `estimateSessionDuration` (raw line parsing for timestamps) and potentially `extractModelFromTranscript` (if model is top-level) need to split raw JSONL data and unmarshal each line. A small helper that yields raw line bytes would reduce duplication.\\n   198→\\n   199→10. **[Task 3, line 267] `CalculateTokenUsage` signature has 5 parameters but plan passes 4.**\\n   200→\\n   201→    The spec (line 90) shows:\\n   202→    ```go\\n   203→    agent.CalculateTokenUsage(ctx, ag, transcriptData, 0)\\n   204→    ```\\n   205→\\n   206→    But the actual signature (`agent/token_usage.go:13`) is:\\n   207→    ```go\\n   208→    func CalculateTokenUsage(ctx context.Context, ag Agent, transcriptData []byte, transcriptLinesAtStart int, subagentsDir string) *TokenUsage\\n   209→    ```\\n   210→\\n   211→    The plan (line 267) correctly passes 5 args:\\n   212→    ```go\\n   213→    agent.CalculateTokenUsage(logCtx, ag, transcriptData, 0, \\\"\\\")\\n   214→    ```\\n   215→\\n   216→    The spec has a bug (4 args). The plan is correct. No action needed -- noting for completeness.\\n   217→\\n   218→### Praise\\n   219→\\n   220→- The plan has been thoroughly revised since review-01. All previous critical issues are resolved. The adoption of `CondenseSessionByID` (via `condenseAndFinalizeSession`) is a much cleaner approach than the original inlined condensation logic.\\n   221→- Good test-driven development structure throughout -- each task writes a failing test first, then implements.\\n   222→- The Gemini fallback pattern (try JSONL first, fall back to Gemini JSON) is consistent and well-structured across all helper functions.\\n   223→- The plan correctly identifies that `agent.CalculateTokenUsage` needs 5 parameters including the empty `subagentsDir`, which the spec missed.\\n   224→\\n   225→## Summary\\n   226→\\n   227→- **Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n   228→- **Key concerns:**\\n   229→  1. **[Critical]** `estimateSessionDuration` parses `line.Message` for timestamps, but `timestamp` is a top-level JSONL field not captured in `transcript.Line.Message`. The function will always return 0. Must parse raw JSONL lines instead.\\n   230→  2. **[Important]** `countUserTurns` will double-count `tool_result` lines that have `\\\"type\\\":\\\"user\\\"`, inflating turn counts for any session with tool usage.\\n   231→  3. **[Suggestion]** The `prompt.txt` test path may be wrong (`.entire/sessions/` vs `.entire/metadata/`). Verify against `paths.SessionMetadataDirFromSessionID`.\\n   232→  4. **[Suggestion]** Verify whether `model` field is inside `message` or at the JSONL line top level in real Claude Code transcripts.\\n   233→- **Estimated effort to address feedback:** 1-2 hours. The timestamp parsing fix requires rewriting `estimateSessionDuration` to use raw line parsing. The double-counting fix requires adding a tool_result filter to `countUserTurns`. Both are straightforward.\\n   234→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"4f2f8555-7168-417e-b07d-22e24630ca43\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-13T18:27:36.539Z\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a80da6d2aa99fb094\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01RFvXM9kgyWXNWiJhh2AxgX\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01BRh4KDot1uBtSD9NLfbu28\",\"uuid\":\"3df5d0df-7c78-4a6a-8e1d-a45deeb7eaf9\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-13T18:27:36.540Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/ninawork/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"1d0832aa-dda4-4240-8c31-8f5c05446140\",\"version\":\"2.1.75\",\"gitBranch\":\"attach-session-id\",\"slug\":\"wild-coalescing-ullman\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"3df5d0df-7c78-4a6a-8e1d-a45deeb7eaf9\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-13T18:27:39.848Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_013e5ibLHy6ze5p2pBswnWHk\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01JqSHPa27pZPUGknavouyjh\",\"name\":\"Read\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/ninawork/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/textutil/strip.go\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":2351,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":74452,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":2351,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\"