/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"1d0832aa-dda4-4240-8c31-8f5c05446140\",\"version\":\"2.1.75\",\"gitBranch\":\"attach-session-id\",\"slug\":\"wild-coalescing-ullman\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"554d5537-7c8a-4104-9020-90f6cd3c2fbe\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"promptId\":\"7df2933f-f2cf-4c12-ae45-2c83e4660a83\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_017uEQ2vDDs1Vn2R78o4u5AH\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here are my findings from the code quality review of `attach.go` and `attach_test.go`:\\n\\n---\\n\\n## attach.go Findings\\n\\n### 1. Repeated transcript parsing (Copy-paste with slight variation)\\n\\n**Lines 396, 465, 492**: `transcript.ParseFromBytes(data)` is called three separate times across `extractFirstPromptFromTranscript`, `countUserTurns`, and `extractModelFromTranscript`. Each function independently parses the same JSONL data, iterates over the lines, and has the same \\\"try JSONL first, fallback to Gemini\\\" structure.\\n\\nAll three functions follow the identical pattern:\\n1. Parse JSONL with `transcript.ParseFromBytes`\\n2. Iterate looking for a specific line type\\n3. Fall back to Gemini format (or return empty)\\n\\nThese could be unified into a single parse-once approach -- either a struct that holds the parsed result, or a single function like `analyzeTranscript(data) -> (firstPrompt, turnCount, model, duration)` that does one pass. This would also eliminate the repeated Gemini fallback logic at lines 409 and 481.\\n\\n### 2. Redundant `os.Stat` calls in `resolveAndValidateTranscript` (Redundant state)\\n\\n**Lines 314 and 322**: The transcript path is stat'd twice. If the fallback search at line 315 succeeds and reassigns `transcriptPath`, the second stat at line 322 re-checks the new path. But `searchTranscriptInProjectDirs` already found a valid file, so the second stat is redundant in the success case. The code structure could be simplified to a single stat after all resolution attempts, or the fallback could return early on success.\\n\\n### 3. Gemini-specific branching with string-typed agent comparison (Leaky abstraction / stringly-typed)\\n\\n**Line 149**: `if agentType == agent.AgentTypeGemini` is a Gemini-specific code path hardcoded into the generic `runAttach` function. If more agents need transcript normalization in the future, this becomes an if/else chain. A cleaner approach would be an optional `NormalizeTranscript(data) ([]byte, error)` method on the `Agent` interface (or a separate interface like `TranscriptNormalizer`), consistent with the existing `TranscriptAnalyzer` pattern used at line 107.\\n\\n### 4. `enrichSessionState` loads/saves state redundantly (Redundant state round-trips)\\n\\n**Lines 240-266**: `enrichSessionState` loads the session state, mutates it, and saves it. Then at line 280 in `condenseAndFinalizeSession`, the state is loaded *again*, mutated, and saved again. That is two load+save cycles in rapid succession. The enrichment and finalization could share a single load/save, or the state object could be threaded through.\\n\\n### 5. `estimateSessionDuration` re-parses raw bytes instead of reusing parsed lines\\n\\n**Lines 515-546**: This function manually splits on newlines and unmarshals each line, duplicating the work that `transcript.ParseFromBytes` does. It needs the `timestamp` field which `transcript.Line` apparently does not expose, but this is a sign the `transcript.Line` type could be extended rather than having parallel parsing logic.\\n\\n### 6. `agentType` derived but also available from `ag`\\n\\n**Line 92**: `agentType := ag.Type()` is called, and then both `ag` and `agentType` are passed around separately. The `agentType` is used at lines 149, 182, 205 while `ag` is used at lines 94, 100, 107, 187. Since `agentType` is always derivable from `ag.Type()`, storing it as a separate variable is minor redundant state. Not critical, but worth noting since it adds cognitive overhead about which