ual (\\\"get first prompt\\\"), not functional. No reuse opportunity here. The two are complementary.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 3. `countUserTurns` (lines 462-486) -- no existing equivalent\\n\\nThe `countUserTurns` function counts user turns from raw transcript bytes. The lifecycle path (`lifecycle.go:840-841`) increments `SessionTurnCount` on each `TurnEnd` event instead. For `attach`, there are no lifecycle events to replay, so counting from the transcript is the only option.\\n\\n**No reuse opportunity.** However, `countUserTurns` calls `extractTextFromMessage` (line 470), and as noted in finding #1, that should be replaced with `transcript.ExtractUserContent`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 4. `estimateSessionDuration` (lines 515-546) -- no existing equivalent\\n\\nThis function parses timestamps from raw JSONL lines. The normal lifecycle path gets duration from hook events (`event.DurationMs` in `lifecycle.go:831`). No existing utility parses timestamps from raw transcript bytes.\\n\\n**No reuse opportunity.** This is attach-specific logic for reconstructing metadata that the lifecycle normally gets from hook events.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 5. `normalizeGeminiTranscript` (lines 448-458) -- no existing equivalent, correctly delegates\\n\\nThis function round-trips through `geminicli.ParseTranscript` to normalize the content format. The normalization itself is handled by `GeminiMessage.UnmarshalJSON` in the `geminicli` package. `attach.go` is correctly delegating to the existing parser rather than reimplementing the normalization.\\n\\n**No reuse opportunity.** The function is a thin wrapper that correctly uses the existing `geminicli` package.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 6. `enrichSessionState` (lines 239-267) -- no existing equivalent\\n\\nThe lifecycle path builds session state incrementally across events (turn start, turn end, model update, session end). `enrichSessionState` is a batch equivalent that populates all fields at once from transcript data. This is inherently different from the event-dri