omBytes`.**\\n\\n   `enrichSessionState` (line 187) calls four functions that each independently re-parse `transcriptData`:\\n\\n   | Function | Line | What it does with `transcriptData` |\\n   |----------|------|------------------------------------|\\n   | `agent.CalculateTokenUsage` | 250 | Agent-specific parsing (e.g., `transcript.ParseFromBytes` inside Claude Code) |\\n   | `countUserTurns` | 253 | Calls `transcript.ParseFromBytes(data)` -- full JSONL parse |\\n   | `extractModelFromTranscript` | 256 | Calls `transcript.ParseFromBytes(data)` -- full JSONL parse |\\n   | `estimateSessionDuration` | 259 | Calls `bytes.Split(data, \\\"\\\\n\\\")` + `json.Unmarshal` per line |\\n\\n   Additionally, before `enrichSessionState` is called, `extractFirstPromptFromTranscript` (line 168) also calls `transcript.ParseFromBytes(data)` -- a 4th full parse.\\n\\n   Each `transcript.ParseFromBytes` call (see `transcript/parse.go:17-47`) creates a `bufio.Reader`, iterates every line, and calls `json.Unmarshal` on each. For a large transcript (thousands of JSONL lines, common in long sessions), this means:\\n\\n   - **4 full scans** of the byte slice\\n   - **3x `json.Unmarshal` per line** (from the 3 `ParseFromBytes` calls) plus 1x per line from `estimateSessionDuration`\\n   - Each parse allocates a fresh `[]Line` slice with all `json.RawMessage` fields\\n\\n   For a 2MB transcript with 500 lines, that is roughly 2000 `json.Unmarshal` calls instead of ~500, and 3 redundant `[]Line` allocations that are immediately discarded.\\n\\n   **Fix:** Parse once, pass the result to all consumers. Create a helper struct or parse the transcript once at the call site in `enrichSessionState`, then pass `[]transcript.Line` to `countUserTurns`, `extractModelFromTranscript`, and `extractFirstPromptFromTranscript`. For `estimateSessionDuration`, since it needs the raw timestamp field not captured by `transcript.Line`, it must do its own raw-line scan -- but that is only 1 extra pass, not 3.\\n\\n   Alternatively, if you want to keep the functions standalone (accepting `[]byte`), add an internal \\\"parsed transcript\\\" type that caches the parse result and is shared across the functions. Either way, the current approach of parsing the same bytes 4 times is wasteful.\\n\\n   Estimated savings: ~60% reduction in CPU time and allocations for transcript processing.\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n2. **[Lines 100 + 108] Double file read of the transcript.**\\n\\n   Line 100: `ag.ReadTranscript(transcriptPath)` reads the entire file into memory.\\n   Line 108: `analyzer.ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset(transcriptPath, 0)` reads the same file from disk again (for Claude Code, see `claudecode/claude.go:308` which calls `os.Open(path)` and reads it line by line).\\n\\n   The transcript is read from disk twice. For large transcripts, this is an unnecessary I/O syscall and buffer allocation. The order could be swapped (read once, pass bytes to both), but the `ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset` interface takes a path, not bytes. This is a design constraint from the `TranscriptAnalyzer` interface.\\n\\n   **Fix (low effort):** Swap the order so `ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset` runs first (it reads from disk), then use `ag.ReadTranscript` to get the bytes. No net savings, but at least the OS page cache will serve the second read. Alternatively, for a larger refactor, add a `ExtractModifiedFilesFromBytes(data []byte, offset int)` method to avoid the second disk read entirely.\\n\\n   This is \\\"Important\\\" rather than \\\"Critical\\\" because the OS page cache mitigates the impact in practice -- the second read is served from memory, not disk. But it is still a wasted syscall and allocation.\\n\\n3. **[Line 149] Gemini transcript parsed 3+ times for Gemini agents.**\\n\\n   For Gemini agents, the flow is:\\n   - `extractFirstPromptFromTranscript` (line 168): tries JSONL parse (fails), then calls `geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts(data)` which calls `geminicli.ParseTranscript(data)` -- **1st Gemini JSON parse**\\n   - `normalizeGeminiTranscript` (line 150): calls `geminicli.ParseTranscript(data)` -- **2nd Gemini JSON parse**\\n   - `countUserTurns` (line 253 via `enrichSessionState`): tries JSONL parse (fails), then calls `geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts(data)` which calls `geminicli.ParseTranscript(data)` -- **3rd Gemini JSON parse**\\n   - `agent.CalculateTokenUsage` (line 250 via `enrichSessionState`): calls `GeminiCLIAgent.CalculateTokenUsage` which calls `json.Unmarshal(transcriptData, &transcript)` -- **4th Gemini JSON parse**\\n\\n   That is 4 full JSON parses of the same Gemini transcript. The `GeminiTranscript` struct is non-trivial (nested messages with tool calls), so each parse is expensive.\\n\\n   **Fix:** For Gemini agents, parse once with `geminicli.ParseTranscript(data)` and thread the parsed struct through the helper functions. The `normalizeGeminiTranscript`, `extractFirstPromptFromTranscript`, and `countUserTurns` functions could all accept a `*GeminiTranscript` when the agent is Gemini-type.\\n\\n4. **[Lines 515-546] `estimateSessionDuration` does a 5th pass over the data with its own line splitting.**\\n\\n   `estimateSessionDuration` calls `bytes.Split(data, []byte(\\\"\\\\n\\\"))` which allocates a `[][]byte` slice holding a reference to every line. For a 500-line transcript, this allocates a 500-element slice. It then calls `json.Unmarshal` on each line just to extract a single `timestamp` field.\\n\\n   This is the only function that needs raw-line access (because `transcript.Line` does not capture `timestamp`). The overhead is acceptable as a single-pass scan, but the `bytes.Split` call is unnecessary -- a `bytes.IndexByte` loop or `bufio.Scanner` would avoid the upfront slice allocation.\\n\\n   **Fix (minor):** Replace `bytes.Split` with a scanning loop:\\n   ```go\\n   for len(remaining) > 0 {\\n       idx := bytes.IndexByte(remaining, '\\\\n')\\n       var rawLine []byte\\n       if idx < 0 {\\n           rawLine = remaining\\n           remaining = nil\\n       } else {\\n           rawLine = remaining[:idx]\\n           remaining = remaining[idx+1:]\\n       }\\n       // ... unmarshal rawLine\\n   }\\n   ```\\n   This avoids allocating the full `[][]byte` slice.\\n\\n5. **[Lines 105-113 + 115-128] No concurrency between transcript analysis and git status.**\\n\\n   `ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset` (line 108) reads and parses the transcript file, while `DetectFileChanges` (line 116) runs `git status`. These are completely independent operations -- one is file I/O + CPU, the other is a subprocess call. They could run concurrently with `errgroup` to shave time off the attach command.\\n\\n   **Fix:**\\n   ```go\\n   g, gctx := errgroup.WithContext(ctx)\\n   var modifiedFiles []string\\n   g.Go(func() error {\\n       if analyzer, ok := agent.AsTranscriptAnalyzer(ag); ok {\\n           files, _, err := analyzer.ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset(transcriptPath, 0)\\n           if err != nil { return nil } // non-fatal\\n           modifiedFiles = files\\n       }\\n       return nil\\n   })\\n   var changes *FileChanges\\n   g.Go(func() error {\\n       var err error\\n       changes, err = DetectFileChanges(gctx, nil)\\n       return err // or nil if non-fatal\\n   })\\n   _ = g.Wait()\\n   ```\\n\\n   Estimated savings: 100-300ms on typical repos (git status latency).\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n6. **[Line 168] `extractFirstPromptFromTranscript` scans the entire transcript but only needs the first user line.**\\n\\n   `transcript.ParseFromBytes` parses every line in the file, but `extractFirstPromptFromTranscript` returns as soon as it finds the first user message. For a 500-line transcript, 499 lines are parsed unnecessarily.\\n\\n   A streaming approach (read line by line, stop at first match) would be more efficient. The `transcript.ParseFromBytes` API does not support early termination.\\n\\n   This is a suggestion because the function is called once 